---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FAQ | hospitalbillnegotiationcalc.com';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about hospital bill negotiation: charity care, billing errors, prompt-pay discounts, and collections.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>Can I really negotiate a hospital bill?</h2>
  <p>Yes. Hospitals routinely accept less than their chargemaster rates. Ask for an itemized bill, identify errors, apply for financial assistance, and request the hospital&rsquo;s &ldquo;self-pay&rdquo; or &ldquo;uninsured&rdquo; rate. Hospitals would rather collect 50 cents on the dollar than send accounts to collections or write them off.</p>
  <h2>What is charity care?</h2>
  <p>Nonprofit hospitals receiving federal tax exemptions must provide free or reduced-cost care to patients who meet income guidelines. Income thresholds vary by hospital but often extend to 200–400% of the federal poverty level. You must apply with proof of income. Charity care can eliminate 100% of the bill.</p>
  <h2>What are the most common medical billing errors?</h2>
  <p>Duplicate charges, upcoding (billing for a more expensive service than provided), unbundling (billing separately for services that should be grouped), incorrect patient information causing insurance denials, charges for services not received, and wrong insurance information. Studies estimate 40–80% of hospital bills contain errors.</p>
  <h2>Will negotiating hurt my credit?</h2>
  <p>Not if you act before the bill goes to collections. Negotiate before the 180-day mark when many hospitals send accounts to collection agencies. Medical debt under $500 was removed from credit reports by the major bureaus in 2023; paid medical debt is removed immediately. Unpaid medical debt over $500 that has been in collections for a year can appear on credit reports.</p>
  <h2>What if my bill is already in collections?</h2>
  <p>You can still negotiate. Collection agencies buy medical debt for 4–10 cents on the dollar, so they have room to settle for 20–40 cents. Get any settlement agreement in writing before paying. Paying a collection agency does not remove the account from your credit report, but the status changes to &ldquo;paid.&rdquo;</p>
</BaseLayout>
